Product Requirements Document (PRD) – AI Threat Hunting & Threat Intelligence Agent
Version: 1.0
1. Introduction
1.1 Purpose: This PRD specifies an autonomous AI-based Threat Intelligence and Hunting Agent that continuously ingests cyber threat feeds, analyzes emerging threats, and delivers actionable intelligence to security teams【10†L90-L94】【8†L284-L290】. The system’s goal is to dramatically shorten time-to-detection by automating manual research – it will actively monitor structured feeds (e.g. NIST NVD, CISA), unstructured sources (e.g. security blogs, GitHub PoCs), and threat platforms to discover new vulnerabilities, malware campaigns, and phishing threats【12†L118-L122】【10†L99-L107】. Generative AI (via LangChain orchestration and Groq-enabled LLMs) will be used not merely to summarize text but to extract technical details (TTPs, IOCs, CVEs) with machine speed, fusing human-like expertise with automation【10†L99-L107】【8†L284-L290】. In doing so, the agent will provide precise CVE summaries, severity scores, exploitation status, detection signatures, and mitigation advice – all in structured reports and on-demand answers to analyst queries.
1.2 Scope: The scope of the Threat Intelligence Agent includes:
Continuous Threat Feed Monitoring: Poll public threat data sources and vulnerabilities (e.g. NVD, CISA KEV, vendor advisories) via APIs to retrieve new CVE records and alerts【12†L118-L122】.
Vulnerability Tracking: Identify and prioritize newly published CVEs, retrieving details (descriptions, references) and computing their CVSS scores (e.g. via the NVD API【2†L125-L132】) to gauge impact.
Ransomware Campaign Summarization: Aggregate information on ongoing ransomware families and campaigns by analyzing threat reports and shared intelligence (using MISP galaxies for ransomware, for example【16†L175-L181】). The agent will extract key indicators (malware samples, hashes, ransom notes) and TTPs from those sources.
Phishing Indicator Analysis: Detect and analyze emerging phishing threats by monitoring email/URL blacklists and scanning domains/IPs through VirusTotal and Shodan. It will flag new malicious domains or phishing kits and gather context (e.g. VT reputation scores【20†L81-L89】).
Data Correlation: Correlate disparate threat data (link CVEs to malware campaigns or phishing, relate TTPs across reports) using an internal knowledge base or vector store. The system will unify duplicate intelligence (e.g. the same exploit reported by multiple sources becomes a single entry【12†L142-L146】) and highlight links between events.
Reporting and Alerts: Generate a daily “Threat Feed Report” summarizing the highest-risk findings (e.g. top CVEs, active exploits, notable campaigns) and send it to stakeholders. It will also respond to analyst queries (e.g. “What are today’s most dangerous vulnerabilities?”) with structured answers that include CVE summaries, CVSS, exploitation status, detection methods, and mitigation recommendations. All outputs will reference source data.
2. Overall Description
The system is architected as a modular, multi-agent framework running on Python. Each agent has a distinct role, coordinated by LangChain orchestration and Groq-backed LLM reasoning:
Threat Intelligence Collector: Continuously fetches the latest threat data. For example, it polls structured feeds (NVD/CISA for CVEs) and scans unstructured sources (security blogs, GitHub for PoCs) using web search APIs【12†L118-L122】. It also retrieves latest malware samples and IOCs from VirusTotal and MISP.
Vulnerability Researcher: Analyzes collected CVEs for severity and exploitation risk. It uses the NVD API to get CVSS scores and descriptions【2†L125-L132】, and may query exploit prediction services (e.g. EPSS) or known-exploit catalogs to determine if a vulnerability is being actively exploited. The LLM “brain” extracts offensive techniques and profiles threat actors, mirroring how a human researcher would interpret vulnerability data【12†L134-L138】【10†L99-L107】.
Phishing and Campaign Analyst: Focuses on malicious campaigns. It processes phishing feeds and identifies patterns (e.g. attacker spoof domains). It also summarizes ransomware campaigns by cross-referencing malware families with recent incidents and using MISP’s Ransomware Galaxy for context【16†L175-L181】.
Incident Response Advisor: Correlates threats with detection and mitigation strategies. Based on the identified threats, it suggests specific detection rules (e.g. YARA signatures, IDS rules) and recommends patches or workarounds. For instance, if a CVE is exploited by a new exploit kit, the agent would note relevant Snort signatures or heuristic detections.
Report Generator: Compiles and formats the intelligence into user-facing outputs. It produces structured Markdown/HTML reports and alerts (daily briefings, dashboards, or Slack notifications). Each threat entry includes CVE details (ID, title, description), CVSS score, exploit status, detection guidance, and mitigation advice【12†L157-L160】【22†L51-L59】. The generator ensures all claims are traceable to sources.
Under the hood, the system uses LangChain to manage the agent workflows and tool calls. Real-time LLM calls (for summarization and reasoning) may use Groq’s high-speed inference API. For example, Groq’s compound-beta agent model supports parallel tool calls (web search, code execution) with minimal latency【26†L119-L128】. A persistent knowledge base (e.g. MongoDB or vector database) stores processed intelligence so that new data is cross-referenced against history【12†L140-L146】. This memory enables semantic deduplication (e.g. multiple blog reports on one exploit become one unified alert) and allows the agent to “remember” previously addressed issues.
3. System Features
3.1 Threat Feed Ingestion: The agent shall continuously pull data from multiple intelligence sources. It will use the NVD CVE API for new vulnerabilities【2†L125-L132】, subscribe to CISA’s Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) feed, and monitor security news/blogs (via web search) for zero-day or ransomware news【12†L118-L122】. It will also integrate malware feeds (e.g. MISP event feeds) and phishing blocklists. The ingestion component cleans and normalizes incoming data into a standardized format for analysis【12†L126-L134】.
3.2 Vulnerability Monitoring: For each new CVE, the system shall retrieve details (title, description, references) and compute its CVSS score. Using the NVD API, it will query by CVE ID or CPE to find affected products【2†L125-L134】. CVEs will be triaged based on severity (e.g. flagging those rated 9–10 as critical). The agent will also query public exploit repositories or EPSS to determine exploitation probability. It will tag CVEs as “Active Exploitation” if evidence (PoC or in-the-wild usage) exists.
3.3 Ransomware Campaign Analysis: The agent will track active ransomware by name (e.g. “LockBit”, “Cl0p”) by scraping security reports and using MISP’s ransomware clusters. It summarizes each campaign’s tactics, known IOCs (e.g. TOR addresses, email patterns), and targets. The LLM component helps extract human-readable summaries of campaign behavior. Ransomware entries in the report will include any CVEs or weaknesses used (e.g. exploited SMB vulnerability) and known ransomware notes for correlation. (MISP maintains a Ransomware Galaxy that can be used to classify threats【16†L175-L181】.)
3.4 Phishing Indicator Detection: The system shall analyze phishing threats by aggregating domain/IP reputation data. It will use VirusTotal’s domain/IP reports to check new suspicious URLs or attachments【20†L81-L89】. When a suspicious email or domain is reported (e.g. via logs or community feeds), the agent calls VirusTotal and Shodan APIs to gather context (e.g. is this domain tied to known malware? what services do its IPs run【18†L35-L43】【20†L81-L89】?). Detected phishing IOCs are correlated with any related campaigns or threat actors. The agent flags spikes in phishing and can highlight targeted brands or sectors.
3.5 Data Correlation and Knowledge: The agent will cross-correlate all gathered data to find connections. For example, it might link a critical CVE to a ransomware variant if that malware uses the exploit, or identify that multiple alerts refer to the same TTP. A key feature is a knowledge base that aggregates historic intelligence. New findings are checked against this memory – as Palo Alto’s design notes, duplicate reports of the same technique from different sources are merged into one entry【12†L140-L146】. By leveraging semantic matching, the system avoids redundant alerts and builds a unified view of ongoing threats.
3.6 Detection Guidance: For each identified threat, the agent provides concrete detection methods. This could include recommended IDS/IPS rules, YARA signatures (suggested via LLM analysis of malware behavior), or configuration checks. The goal is to translate each threat into something actionable – for example, if CVE-XXXX-YYYY allows remote code execution, the agent might suggest scanning logs for a specific exploit string or enabling a vendor patch that addresses the root cause.
3.7 Mitigation Recommendations: Alongside detection, the system shall output mitigation advice. This typically means citing vendor patches, configuration changes, or workarounds for each CVE or campaign. For instance, a CVE entry will list the fixed versions (from NVD references) or firewall rules to block malicious traffic. All recommendations will be drawn from trusted sources (e.g. vendor advisories, CVE references) and formatted as clear action items for analysts.
3.8 Reporting and User Interface: The agent will assemble a daily threat report (see Appendix) that lists top vulnerabilities and incidents with summaries. Reports will be generated in a structured format (Markdown/HTML) and may be delivered via email, Slack, or a web dashboard. Additionally, a user-facing query interface (CLI or web chat) allows analysts to ask questions. The agent responds conversationally, citing its sources for each claim (as emphasized in one implementation: “Every claim traces to a source you can verify”【22†L86-L90】).
4. External Interface Requirements
NVD CVE API (REST/JSON): The system will use the NVD API v2.0/2.0c to fetch CVE details by ID or CPE【2†L125-L132】. Endpoints support filtering by CVE ID, CPE name, CVSS scores, etc. The agent must handle pagination (NVD uses offset paging) and may require an API key for higher rate limits.
VirusTotal API v3 (REST/JSON): For malware and URL analysis, the agent will integrate VirusTotal v3 endpoints【20†L71-L79】. Key endpoints include file/URL upload and report (using file hashes or URLs), domain report, and IP report. These return aggregated detection results from 70+ AV engines and sandbox analyses.
Shodan API: The agent will use Shodan’s REST API to gather Internet asset data【18†L35-L43】. This includes IP/host search (to see open ports, services, and known vulnerabilities) and the Shodan “Data Stream” feature to receive real-time alerts on new vulnerabilities or configurations【18†L35-L43】【18†L42-L45】.
MISP REST API (PyMISP): Integration with a MISP instance via its REST API allows the agent to fetch and upload threat intelligence (events, attributes, IOCs)【16†L200-L204】. The Python library PyMISP will be used for convenient access. The agent can pull community event feeds and also store its own reports back into MISP for sharing.
LLM API (LangChain/GROQ): The system will call an LLM service for analysis tasks. This may be OpenAI’s API or Groq’s cloud inference API. Groq’s compound-beta agent models (via the Groq API) support simultaneous tool use (web search, Python execution) for building an “AI research agent”【26†L119-L128】. The LangChain framework will structure prompts, handle tool calls, and manage conversation state.
User Query Interface: The agent exposes a query interface (could be a CLI, REST endpoint, or chatbot) for analysts to ask questions. It also formats reports for human consumption (e.g. CLI output or Slack messages). All user-facing text must be clear, concise, and include source references.
5. Other Non-Functional Requirements
Performance: The daily analysis pipeline (ingestion ➔ analysis ➔ report generation) should complete within a target window (e.g. 1 hour off-hours). LLM calls should be optimized for speed (leveraging Groq’s low-latency inference【26†L119-L128】).
Reliability: The system must handle upstream failures gracefully. If an API call fails or rate-limits, the agent should retry with backoff or queue for the next cycle. Processed data should be checkpointed (e.g. in a local database) so that interruptions do not lose progress.
Accuracy & Traceability: All intelligence must be accurate and verifiable. In practice, the agent will flag only high-confidence findings. Crucially, it must cite sources for every claim – for example, every CVE detail or exploitation note should link back to the original advisory or report. As one implementation notes, having visible tool calls and sources is essential for security analysts【22†L86-L90】.
Security: The system handles only public threat data, but API keys and any credentials (MISP, VirusTotal keys) must be securely stored (e.g. encrypted environment variables). Communications with APIs will use HTTPS. The agent must not expose any internal secrets in its reports.
Scalability: The design should allow adding more data sources or analysis modules over time. It should support concurrent query handling (e.g. multiple analysts querying at once) without deadlocks. Horizontal scaling (e.g. running multiple collector threads or LLM workers) is desirable for larger deployments.
Maintainability: Code will be modular and documented. The knowledge base should allow easy updates (e.g. updating ML embeddings or rule sets). Logging and monitoring will be implemented (e.g. track count of CVEs processed, errors).
User Acceptability: Reports and answers must be human-readable. Technical jargon should be explained, and summaries kept concise (a few sentences per threat). The system should adhere to security team workflows (e.g. integrate with Slack or ticketing).
6. Appendix
6.1 Sample Analyst Query and Agent Response
User: “What are today’s most dangerous vulnerabilities?”
Agent Response (example):
CVE-2026-34567 – Remote Code Execution in AcmeWeb 4.2: A critical path-traversal flaw in AcmeWeb allows attackers to upload and execute arbitrary files. CVSS: 9.8 (Critical). Exploitation: Confirmed. This exploit has appeared in underground forums, and an open Proof-of-Concept is circulating. Detection: IDS signatures for the exploit URI and file-write behavior are available; network traffic logs should be checked for unusual POST requests to /upload. Mitigation: Upgrade AcmeWeb to 4.2.1 (vendor patch) or disable the vulnerable file-upload feature as per vendor advisory.
CVE-2026-45678 – Authentication Bypass in QuickStore CMS: An auth bypass in QuickStore v2.x enables privilege escalation. CVSS: 8.7 (High). Exploitation: Likely/Potential. No public exploit yet, but attackers may weaponize it soon. Detection: Look for suspicious admin access patterns; unusual logins. Mitigation: Apply the hotfix from QuickStore (update to v2.1) and review admin access controls.
6.2 Daily Threat Report Template
Date: 2026-07-02 Target: AcmeCorp Production Environment
New Critical CVEs:
CVE-2026-34567 (AcmeWeb 4.2) – See summary above. (Critical RCE, active exploit)
CVE-2026-45678 (QuickStore CMS) – High-severity auth bypass; monitor for exploit.
Ransomware Campaigns:
LockBit v9: New variant using a novel scheduler evasive technique. Qakbot families observed as loaders. (Indicators: SHA256 abc..., domains pay.lockbit.io).
RhinoCrypt: Targeting financial sector; uses CVE-2026-12345 (Office doc RCE) to propagate. Block associated file hashes.
Phishing Alerts:
Domain: secure-acmecorp.com – Spoofs AcmeCorp portal. Identified via DNS monitoring. (VT score 75/100). Add to blocklist and educate users.
Email: Fake invoice messages with attachment invoice_0702.doc (SHA256 def...) – Detected by VT and YARA rule based on known maldoc template.
Correlation Notes: Several alerts reference CVE-2026-34567 – this CVE was exploited by LockBit v9 as an initial entry vector. Our EDR should already block this path if patched.
Recommended Actions:
Apply critical patches (AcmeWeb 4.2.1, QuickStore 2.1) immediately.
Update network IDS with LockBit scheduler and AcmeWeb exploit signatures.
Block phishing domain and hashes in email gateway.
Review user login anomalies (related to QuickStore auth bypass).
7. Glossary
CVE (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures): A standardized identifier for a known software vulnerability.
CVSS (Common Vulnerability Scoring System): A numerical score (0.0–10.0) indicating the severity of a CVE.
IOC (Indicator of Compromise): Artifacts (e.g. file hashes, IP addresses, domains) observed on a network or system indicating malicious activity.
TTP (Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures): A high-level description of an adversary’s behavior or method (e.g. “SQL Injection” or “Privilege Escalation via DLL hijack”).
LLM (Large Language Model): An AI model (like GPT or Groq’s Llama-based models) used for understanding or generating human-like text.
YARA Rule: A pattern-matching rule used to identify malware or malicious files by their characteristics.
8. Acceptance Criteria
The system shall be considered successful if all of the following are met:
Timeliness: New high-risk vulnerabilities and threats are detected and included in the daily report with minimal delay.
Accuracy: Each CVE entry includes a correct summary and CVSS rating, and exploit status (confirmed or not) based on reliable sources.
Actionability: Reports and answers consistently include actionable data (e.g. detection signatures, patch steps). In practice, outputs resemble a curated threat feed, not just raw CVE lists【12†L157-L160】.
Completeness: All user queries (e.g. “top vulnerabilities”) are answered with structured information (CVE, CVSS, exploitation, detection, mitigation) and cite their sources. (As shown in a sample run, the agent provides each claim with a reference【22†L86-L90】.)
Reliability: The system runs scheduled reports daily without failures and handles API issues gracefully. Logged tool calls and citations are visible for auditing.
Security Compliance: All API keys are used securely, and no sensitive internal data is leaked. The agent’s recommendations align with official advisories and best practices.
9. Conclusion
This AI Threat Hunting & Threat Intelligence Agent will enhance the security operations team’s ability to stay ahead of fast-moving threats. By automating data collection and leveraging LLM-driven analysis, it provides a scalable “digital analyst” that turns overwhelming threat data into concise, prioritized intelligence. The end goal is to replace reactive chasing of CVEs with a proactive, AI-driven pipeline – effectively turning raw intelligence into real-time defensive action.
Sources: Official API docs and industry research on AI-driven threat intelligence【10†L90-L94】【12†L118-L122】【8†L284-L290】【22†L51-L59】【16†L200-L204】【18†L35-L43】【20†L71-L79】【26†L119-L128】.
